#  Module 01 Study Notes — Alert Priority Levels

## Key Takeaways

1. **CVSS is a baseline** — always combine with asset criticality and business context.
2. **CISA KEV catalog** is gold — if a CVE is there, treat it as Critical regardless of CVSS.
3. **False positives waste analyst time** — use threat intelligence to validate before escalating.
4. **Document your reasoning** — write WHY you assigned a priority level.

## Memory Aid: CVSS Mnemonics

```
"A Crab Patiently Sat Counting Insects Attending"
 |   |   |         |    |        |       |
AV  AC  PR        UI  Scope     CIA      A
```

## Wazuh Rule Priority Mapping

```xml
<!-- Wazuh rule severity -- SOC priority -->
Level  1-4  - Low
Level  5-8  - Medium  
Level  9-12  - High
Level 13-15 - Critical
```

## Quick CVSS Reference Card

```
CRITICAL:  9.0 – 10.0  - Respond IMMEDIATELY (< 1 hour)
HIGH:      7.0 – 8.9   - Respond URGENTLY    (< 4 hours)
MEDIUM:    4.0 – 6.9   - Respond SOON        (< 24 hours)
LOW:       0.1 – 3.9   - Schedule response   (< 1 week)
```

## Study Resources

| Resource | Type | URL |
|----------|------|-----|
| CVSS v3.1 Guide | Documentation | https://www.first.org/cvss/ |
| NVD CVE Database | Tool | https://nvd.nist.gov |
